[5] Indiana (Marion County): hobby/non-poultry flock
Date: Thu 30 Jun 2022
Source: WRTV [edited]
https://www.wrtv.com/news/avian-flu-case-reported-in-marion-county


Avian flu cases reported in Marion County
-----------------------------------------
On [30 Jun 2022], the Indiana State Board of Animal Health (BOAH) reported a hobby/non-poultry flock in Marion County tested positive for the H5 avian influenza virus.

The hobby flock included a goose and a chicken.

They were tested after 2 wild birds in the area tested positive for HPAI.

As a result, local flocks in the surrounding areas need to be tested to ensure the virus has not spread.

BOAH staff said they will be reaching out to poultry owners within the surveillance zone to schedule testing as part of required area surveillance.

The BOAH report listed 9 commercial flocks in surrounding areas, but all their control areas have been lifted. They are cleared to restock poultry at the owners' discretion.

Wild bird surveillance is also working to monitor conditions of non-flock environments. They have sampled nearly 300 wild bird species in the area. So far positive tests have come back from 2 bald eagles, 2 red-tailed hawks, a redhead duck, 2 great-horned owls and a double-crested cormorant.

The wild bird species most likely to carry HPAI are waterbirds and raptors which do not typically visit bird feeders.

The BOAH advises hobby poultry owners should be aware of the signs of avian influenza and report illness and/or death to the USDA Healthy Birds Hotline.

The signs of avian influenza include:
- sudden death without clinical signs
- lack of energy or appetite
- decreased egg production
- soft-shelled or misshapen eggs
- swelling or purple discoloration of head eyelids, comb and hocks
- nasal discharge
- coughing
- sneezing
- lack of coordination
- diarrhea

Avian influenza does not present a food safety risk for people and poultry and eggs are safe to eat. Officials are not aware of any public health significance with this virus and no human cases have been reported.

[Byline: Maddie Heineman]

